node.text: The most essential worm in my box! If I had to give up every finesse worm but keep one, I’ll keep my Jobu! These are my favorite finesse worms and they constantly get bites all year round! My favorite colors are Oxeblood red flake, Watermelon Candy, and Neptune Shad! The Captain over at @c3__baits can custom make you any color you want! Send a DM to @c3__baits and buy a couple bags!

Everyone needs to take a break from the new and improved baits on the market and try going back to the basics. If you can’t get a bite, just throw the drop shot with roboworm. Throw the senko. Throw the classic Ned rig.

node.text: The most essential worm in my box! If I had to give up every finesse worm but keep one, I’ll keep my Jobu! These are my favorite finesse worms and they constantly get bites all year round! My favorite colors are Oxeblood red flake, Watermelon Candy, and Neptune Shad! The Captain over at @c3__baits can custom make you any color you want! Send a DM to @c3__baits and buy a couple bags!

node.text:
When it comes to finesse fishing, I always use 6lb @sunline_america FC Sniper. I find myself using it for a ton of techniques. It is thin enough to be stealthy but strong enough to pull the boat to shore. Anything lower than that gets a little dangerous for me but 6lb has been my workhorse!

node.text:
I honestly hate casting reels… i don’t see much a point in it unless it’s for a Alabama rig, Lipless, or anything that you don’t want to sink so fast. I get way longer of a cast with a spinning reel and when my drag gets pulled, I hear an audible “clicking” noise. The Curado DC isn’t a miracle worker and I still have to tune them in. My Shimano Sahara ($80) spinning reels have been my workhorses without any problems! I’ll throw jigs, spinner baits, and top waters on them all day long. I’m tired of constantly tuning, blowing up, and having shorter casts with a casting reel.
